05087nam a22007455i 9781400873616DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152018nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2015934773  a(OCoLC)984546878  a97814008736167 a10.1515/97814008736162doi  a(DE-B1597)460012  a(OCoLC)916920226  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aQL76.5.U6bG73 2015 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a636.082231 aGrazian, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerican Zoo :bA Sociological Safari /cDavid Grazian.  aPilot project,eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. The World in a Zoo -- t1. Where the Wild Things Aren't: Exhibiting Nature in American Zoos -- t2. Animal Farm: Making Meaning at the Zoo -- t3. Birds of a Feather: Zookeepers and the Call of the Wild -- t4. Life Lessons: The Zoo as a Classroom -- t5. Bring on the Dancing Horses: American Zoos in the Entertainment Age -- t6. Simply Nature: Zoos and the Branding of Conservation -- t7. Wrestling with Armadillos: Animal Welfare and the Captivity Question -- t8. The Urban Jungle: The Future of the American Zoo -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOrangutans swing from Kevlar-lined fire hoses. Giraffes feast on celebratory birthday cakes topped with carrots instead of candles. Hi-tech dinosaur robots growl among steel trees, while owls watch animated cartoons on old television sets. In American Zoo, sociologist David Grazian takes us on a safari through the contemporary zoo, alive with its many contradictions and strange wonders.Trading in his tweed jacket for a zoo uniform and a pair of muddy work boots, Grazian introduces us to zookeepers and animal rights activists, parents and toddlers, and the other human primates that make up the zoo's social world. He shows that in a major shift away from their unfortunate pasts, American zoos today emphasize naturalistic exhibits teeming with lush and immersive landscapes, breeding programs for endangered animals, and enrichment activities for their captive creatures. In doing so, zoos blur the imaginary boundaries we regularly use to separate culture from nature, humans from animals, and civilization from the wild. At the same time, zoos manage a wilderness of competing priorities-animal care, education, scientific research, and recreation-all while attempting to serve as centers for conservation in the wake of the current environmental and climate-change crisis. The world of the zoo reflects how we project our own prejudices and desires onto the animal kingdom, and invest nature with meaning and sentiment.A revealing portrayal of comic animals, delighted children, and feisty zookeepers, American Zoo is a remarkable close-up exploration of a classic cultural attraction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAnimal welfarezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aCaptive wild animalsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aWildlife conservationxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aZoo animalsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aZoosxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aZooszUnited StatesxEmployees. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400873616zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400873616423Coveruhtt